g.title: Folded Corner
g.desc: The Abstract Factory pattern ‘forces’ products to be created ...

g.text: The Abstract Factory pattern ‘forces’ products to be created as a group. An Abstract Factory consists of related objects. These objects may not be used in combination with other objects, other then specified by the respective Factory. E.g. a Windows UI element should not be mixed with a Mac element, because it might result in odd layouts or even malfunctions during mutual interaction. The Abstract Factory overcomes this by constraining the client. A client, injected with an Abstract Factory, can only construct the related products enforced by that Factory. The constrain clarifies design intent, which results in ‘ease-of-use’ on client side. Also, the chance of introducing malfunctions in code base becomes smaller.

g.title: Folded Corner.15
g.desc: The Abstract Factory compliments the Single Responsibility Pr...

g.text: The Abstract Factory compliments the Single Responsibility Principle by separating dependency creation from a class’s primary responsibility. This enhances the readability, reusability, testability and stability of the code base. All aspects are compared against an implementation where a class creates is dependencies internally. Readability, because the (complex) dependency construction logic is ‘distilled’ from the class’s primary responsibility. This makes the class more ‘focused’. Reusability, because the construction logic can be shared with other clients. In contrast, situating the construction logic within the class it self complicates sharing. Sharing might be possible in this case via the Factory Method design pattern. However, this can lead clients to depend on other functionality of that class, functionality they do not need (=violation of ISP). In addition to the reusability aspect, the software system will become more flexibility to change when applying the Abstract Factory pattern. The concrete dependencies are instantiated in a single place and distributed across the system. This means the system only has to change in a single place to swap the objects that are used. In contrast, distributing concrete object creation (duplication) across the code base, makes it harder to change it later. Testability, because the separation of object construction (=Abstract Factory) enables a class to be injected with its dependencies. Dependency injection in combination with an abstraction (e.g. an Abstract Factory) allows mock-ability. Mock-ability enables isolated testing. Isolated testing means the problem window ‘shrinks’ and bugs can be found faster. In contrast, instantiating the dependencies directly within the respective class will cause the problem window to grow. Stability, because construction logic is not directly affected when a class is modified in its primary responsibility and vice versa. The construction logic is separated from the class/client. This minimizes the chance of breaking code unrelated to the change. Additionally, the Abstract Factory constrains the client in construction of possible object combinations. The client is not able to construct unrelated objects, which might cause malfunctions in the sytem.

g.title: Folded Corner.20
g.desc: The Abstract Factory pattern compliments the Open Closed Prin...

g.text: The Abstract Factory pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by allowing the dependencies of a system to change with relative minimal change. This enhances the stability and reusability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where concrete objects are constructed across the code base. Stability, because the dependencies a system works with can be changed from a centralized place. This means two things. First, a single object (Abstract Factory) created once, ensures replacement of multiple objects. The system will have to change in single place, the instantiation of the Factory, to replace multiple Products. In contrast, clients instantiating concrete products across the code base would result in change in multiple places. Secondly, the Products the Factory creates are behind an abstraction as well. This allows new products to be introduced without altering code that uses these products. In contrast, instantiating the concrete products within the clients requires not only to replace all the concrete product instantiations, but also the code where they are used. The Abstract Factory contributes to the stability aspect of the code by minimizing change, which reduces the chance of breaking stable existing product and test code. Reusability, because clients, dependent on an Abstract Factory and Products, can be reused with different concrete Factories and Products. I.e. duplication is reduced, because clients dependent on abstractions instead of concrete details. In contrast, clients being dependent on the concrete implementation directly degrade their reusability.

g.title: Folded Corner.41
g.desc: The Abstract Factory pattern allows a system to change relate...

g.text: The Abstract Factory pattern allows a system to change related, sets of objects via a single object. A common problem is that related objects are created across the code base. In case one of these objects changes, all of the related objects require to change as well. E.g. an application that should support both Mac and Windows UI representations. The Buttons and Textboxes that are used by Windows and Mac OS are not interchangeable. The initial intuition to solve this problem might be to introduce decision logic and concrete instantiation of Windows and Mac OS textboxes & buttons in multiple places of the code base. However, this increases the maintenance effort, making it less flexible to change. The Abstract Factory pattern prescribes to centralize this object creation. One Mac Factory and one Windows Factory. These concrete factories both inherit from the same Abstract Factory and create the corresponding Buttons and Textboxes. The Textboxes and Buttons also follow a common base class. The concrete factory is created once and distribute into the system via its Abstraction. The system can now change its layout by substituting a single object instead of multiple. The decision logic to determine which OS is being used can also be centralized.

g.title: Folded Corner.67
g.desc: The Abstract Factory pattern prescribes delegation of object ...

g.text: The Abstract Factory pattern prescribes delegation of object creation to a separate class. A common situation is a class instantiating all its dependencies internally. This does not allow the flexibility to change the dependencies of a class and ‘blurs’ its primary responsibility (e.g. complex construction logic or an extensive amount of objects must be created). The Abstract Factory pattern proposes to separate the dependency creation from the class’s primary logic (which is different from the Factory Method pattern). The class solely responsible for object creation, is called the Abstract Factory. The Abstract Factory, as the name indicates, is abstract and must be implemented by its sub-classes. The concrete Factories create the corresponding dependencies, called Products. The Products follow an abstraction as well. The abstractions allow clients to remain ‘untouched’ when the system needs to dependent on a new Factory, that constructs different concrete Products.

g.title: Folded Corner.75
g.desc: The Factory Method pattern might be used prior to introducing...

g.text: The Factory Method pattern might be used prior to introducing the Abstract Factory. The Factory Method pattern allows flexibility in the dependencies a class works with, just like the Abstract Factory. The Factory Method pattern is simpler than the Abstract Factory, especially if there is already an existing Creator inheritance hierarchy. However, it might be beneficial to switch to the Abstract Factory when more Factory Methods are added to the Creator and other clients become dependent on the Creator as well. More Factory Methods will ‘blur’ the primary responsibility of the Creator, so delegation of the construction logic to a separate class might help to keep the Creator more ‘focused’ (SRP). More clients, besides the Creator, becoming dependent on the Factory methods may lead clients to become dependent on Creator functionality they don’t use (violation of ISP). Introduction of a class, dedicated to object creation (=Abstract Factory), resolves this problem.

g.title: Folded Corner.79
g.desc: The Abstract Factory entails both the negative and positive s...

g.text: The Abstract Factory entails both the negative and positive side of the Single Responsibility principle. Delegating object creation to a separate class (the Abstract Factory) introduces an additional form of indirection. The client will be more decoupled from its dependencies making the code more scattered. It will be harder to comprehend the exact dependency model of a client, because we must first navigate to the Factory.

g.title: Folded Corner.82
g.desc: The Abstract Factory entails both the negative and positive s...

g.text: The Abstract Factory entails both the negative and positive side of the Open Closed Principle. The Abstract Factory prescribes to define an Abstraction between client and Factory, but also between Product and client. These indirections have negative impact on the navigability and debuggability of the code. In case the flexibility to replace the Factory and/or products is not required, but a client would still like to delegate object creation, then a Simple Factory might be more appropriate solution.
